        <p>Next, we look at an example where a vertial line is used.</p>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Scenario</title>

            <p>Effie, Ivan and Cleo are in a race. The following graph models their distance from the starting point in the first few seconds. Find each person's distance <m>3</m> seconds into the race.</p>
        </paragraphs>

        <figure>
            <caption>Three People's Distance from the Stating Point</caption>
            <image>
            <description>This is a grid with 3 lines to model 3 people's distance from the starting line. Effie's line passes (0,0) and (3,4). This line is colored blue. Ivan's line passes (0,0) and (1,2). This line is colored red. Cleo's line passes (0,0) and (1,3). This line is colored black. A green vertical line goes from (3,-1) to (3,10). This line intersects with Effie's line at (3,4), with Ivan's line at (3,6), with Cleo's line at (3,9).</description>
            <latex-image-code>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[
                        xlabel={seconds},ylabel={meters},
                        xmin=-1,xmax=6,ymin=-1,ymax=10,
                        minor ytick=,
                        minor xtick=,
                        xtick={0,1,...,5},ytick={0,1,...,9}
                    ]
                          \addplot[
                            domain = 0:6,
                            ->,
                            smooth,
                            thin,
                            color = blue,
                          ]{4/3*x};
                          \node at (axis cs: 5,7) [color = blue] {Effie};
                          \addplot[soliddot, color=blue] coordinates {(3, 4)} node[right] {(3,4)};

                          \addplot[
                            domain = 0:5,
                            ->,
                            smooth,
                            thin,
                            color = red,
                          ]{2*x};
                          \node at (axis cs: 4,8) [color = red] {Ivan};
                          \addplot[soliddot, color=red] coordinates {(3, 6)} node[right] {(3,6)};

                          \addplot[
                            domain = 0:10/3,
                            ->,
                            smooth,
                            thin,
                            color = brown,
                          ]{3*x};
                          \node at (axis cs: 2,8) [color = brown] {Cleo};
                          \addplot[soliddot, color=brown] coordinates {(3, 9)} node[right] {(3,9)};

                          \draw[color=black, <->] (axis cs: 3,-1) -- (axis cs: 3,10);
                          \node at (axis cs: 3,1) [left, color = black] {$x=3$};
                    \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
            </latex-image-code>
            </image>
        </figure>

        <p>The black vertial line crosses those three lines at <m>(3,4), (3,6)</m> and <m>(3,9)</m>. They imply: <m>3</m> seconds into the race, Effie was <m>4</m> meters away from the starting point, Ivan was <m>6</m> meters away, and Cleo was <m>9</m> meters away. The vertical line is used to check each line's <m>y</m>-value when <m>x=3\text{.}</m></p>

    </subsection>

